Introduction to R Shiny

Shiny is an open source R package that provides an elegant and powerful framework for building web applications using R language. You can explore examples of web applications created using Shiny in https://www.rstudio.com/products/shiny/.

Shiny is a perfect tool to get a better understanding of concepts such as confidence interval (CI). A confidence interval comes with many components which play distinct roles in determining its properties. In this assignment, the interactive feature of Shiny will allow you to experiment with various choices of each component and observe how the intervals change.

An R Shiny project can be embedded into a website and shared through its URL, or it can be rendered by your own RStudio by running the source code. This tutorial will walk you through the latter method.

Step 3: install required packages

An R Shiny file opens as a regular R script. You must first make sure all the necessary packages required by the file are installed on your copy of R/RStudio. The file CI_Simulator_Shiny.R uses three packages, shiny,ggplot2, and gridExtra.

ggplot2 should already be installed in your RStudio from previous computer assignments. To install the other two, run install.packages("shiny") and install.packages("gridExtra") in the console. You can also do this in one line of code, using install.packages(c("shiny", "gridExtra")).

In general, it is customary to list the loading command library() of all external packages at the beginning of a script. When using an R Shiny app, or any other R script written by others, check the first lines to see if you need to install any packages.

Step 4: run the app

Click Run App in the upper right corner of the script window.

Step 5: you are ready to use the app

A new window will open containing the rendered app.

Part 1: Exploring Confidence Intervals with the Shiny App CI Simulator

Confidence intervals provide a range of plausible values for an unknown population parameter (like the mean or proportion) and are a fundamental tool in statistical inference. They offer a way to quantify the uncertainty inherent in sample-based estimates. This Shiny app enables you to simulate the generation of confidence intervals under various statistical settings, including different population distributions, sample sizes, and methods of interval estimation. Through simulation, you can visually explore how often these intervals capture the true parameter value, an exercise that reinforces the concept of confidence level and the reliability of interval estimates.

When you open the CI Simulator Shiny app, youll find a sidebar with options to set parameters for your simulation. Upon clicking the Sample button the results of the simulation will be displayed in the main panel to the right of the sidebar.

Setting Parameters

  • Method: Choose the method for calculating confidence intervals. Options include z sigma known, z sigma unknown (using s), and t. The choice depends on whether the population standard deviation (sigma) is known and the sample size.

  • Distribution: Select the distribution of your data. Choices are Normal, Uniform, Exponential, and Poisson.

  • Population Parameters:

    • Normal Distribution: The mean (\(\mu\)) and standard deviation (\(\sigma\)).
    • Uniform Distribution: The minimum (\(a\)) and maximum (\(b\)) bounds of the support.
    • Exponential Distribution: The rate parameter (\(\lambda\)).
    • Poisson Distribution: The rate parameter (\(\lambda\)).

  • Sample Size (\(n\)): Choose the number of observations used for each sample.

  • Number of Intervals: Decide how many confidence intervals to generate in the simulation.

  • Confidence Level: Set the confidence level for your intervals, such as 95%.

After setting your parameters, press the Sample button to generate the confidence intervals.

Interpreting Results

The main panel will update to show three plots:

  • Confidence Intervals: In this plot, each confidence interval is represented by an error bar, which denotes the margin of error around the sample mean. The error bars are colored green if they include the true population mean, indicating a successful capture, and red if they do not. Theoretically, the proportion of green error bars should approximate the confidence level youve set (for example, 95%). Note that actual coverage may differ from the expected level, influenced by sample size and population distribution.

  • Most Recent Sample Means: A histogram of the means from the most recent set of samples.

  • Sampling Distribution of the Sample Mean: A histogram of all the sample means collected during repeated simulations.

Below the confidence interval plot, youll see text indicating how many of the simulated intervals contained the population mean, both for the most recent set of intervals and running total. This gives you an intuitive feel for the concept of confidence levels.

Resetting the Simulation: If you want to start over or try different parameters, simply press the Reset button to clear all plots and results.

Key Observations for Students

As you navigate through the CI Simulator Shiny app and engage with the process of generating and analyzing confidence intervals, here are important elements to observe and consider:

  • Variability of Interval Width: Pay attention to how the width of confidence intervals changes with different confidence levels.

  • Sample Size Impact: Observe the effect of sample size on the confidence intervals.

  • Coverage Accuracy: The proportion of confidence intervals that contain the true population mean should approximate the chosen confidence level (e.g., 95%). However, this may not always be the case, especially with smaller sample sizes or non-normal distributions.

  • Method Selection: Consider how the method chosen for calculating confidence intervals (z sigma known, z sigma unknown (using s), or t) affects the interval outcomes. The correct method should be used based on whether the population standard deviation is known and if the sample size is small. The app allows you to dynamically switch between methods to compare how each one constructs intervals based on the same simulation data.

  • Distribution Type: Different data distributions can influence the shape and spread of confidence intervals. Compare the intervals generated under normal, uniform, exponential, and Poisson distributions to see these effects in action. Pay close attention to the

  • Statistical Assumptions: Be aware of the underlying assumptions for each method and distribution. Understanding these assumptions will help you determine when and how the results may vary from expected outcomes.

  • Empirical vs.Theoretical: Through simulation, you can gain insight into the empirical application of statistical theory. Comparing simulated results with theoretical expectations.

Make sure to critically analyze these observations to enhance your statistical reasoning and ability to interpret confidence intervals in practical scenarios.

Part 2: Exploring Statistical Power with the Power Analysis Visualization Applet

You will explore the factors affecting statistical power and error rates using the Power Analysis Visualization Applet. You will manipulate the mean values under null and alternative hypotheses, adjust the significance level (alpha), vary sample sizes, and observe the impact of these changes on Power, Type I and Type II errors.

Setting Parameters

  • Null Mean: Set the assumed population mean when the null hypothesis is true (no effect).

  • Alternative Mean: Set the expected population mean under the alternative hypothesis (presence of effect).

  • Alpha (\(\alpha\)): Set the Type I error rate, the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis when it is actually true.

  • Sample Size (\(n\)): Choose the number of observations that would be sampled.

  • Population Standard Deviation (\(\sigma\)): Select the populations standard deviation, which is assumed to be the same under both the null and alternative hypotheses.

  • Hypothesis Direction: Choose the direction for the hypothesis test:

    • Left-tailed: Use when the alternative hypothesis mean is expected to be less than the null hypothesis mean.
    • Right-tailed: Use when the alternative hypothesis mean is expected to be greater than the null hypothesis mean.
    • Two-tailed: Use when the alternative hypothesis mean could be either less than or greater than the null hypothesis mean.

After setting your parameters, the plots will automatically be updated.

Interpreting Results

The main panel will display two distinct normal distribution curves corresponding to the null and alternative hypothesis means, each clearly annotated. The area shaded in green represents the power of the test, indicating the likelihood of correctly rejecting the null hypothesis when it is false. The red shaded area denotes the Type I error, the probability of erroneously rejecting a true null hypothesis, while the purple shaded area signifies the Type II error, the chance of failing to reject a false null hypothesis.

Key Observations for Students

You are encouraged to explore and note significant insights and takeaways from the Power Analysis Visualization Applet. Pay close attention to how changes in the input parameters affect the shaded regions and the shape of the distributions. Key observations may include:

  • The impact of altering the null and alternative mean values on the power of the test and the positioning of the distribution curves.
  • The relationship between the alpha level and the size of the red shaded region, which represents the Type I error rate.
  • How variations in sample size influence the green shaded region, reflecting the tests power, and the standard error of the distribution.
  • The effect of changing the population standard deviation on the spread of the distribution curves and the subsequent error rates.
  • The implications of selecting different hypothesis directions (left-tailed, right-tailed, two-tailed) on the critical value cutoffs and shaded error regions.
  • Use these observations to deepen your understanding of statistical hypothesis testing, specifically how each factor contributes to the probability of making correct or incorrect inferences about the population based on sample data.
